# Computer Science Basics O/X
> Fundamental computing concepts
@languageCode: en
// Swiq — https://swiq.jiun.dev/set/seed.en.exam-computer.basic/

CPU stands for Central Processing Unit. | O | The CPU, or Central Processing Unit, carries out a computer's instructions.
One byte consists of 16 bits. | X | One byte is 8 bits, not 16.
RAM is a type of volatile memory that loses data when power is off. | O | RAM is volatile, so its contents disappear once power is cut.
HTML is a programming language used to manage databases. | X | HTML is a markup language for web pages; databases use languages like SQL.
Windows, macOS, and Linux are examples of operating systems. | O | These are all widely used operating systems.
A monitor is a primary input device. | X | A monitor is an output device that displays information.
The binary system uses only the digits 0 and 1. | O | Binary represents data using just 0 and 1.
HTTPS is less secure than HTTP. | X | HTTPS encrypts data, making it more secure than HTTP.
An algorithm is a step-by-step procedure to solve a problem. | O | An algorithm is an ordered set of steps for solving a problem.
Software refers to the physical components of a computer. | X | Physical parts are hardware; software refers to programs and code.
A firewall helps protect a network from unauthorized access. | O | A firewall blocks unauthorized traffic to protect a network.
DNS translates IP addresses into physical printer locations. | X | DNS translates human-readable domain names into IP addresses.
A compiler translates source code into machine code. | O | A compiler converts human-readable source code into machine code a computer can run.
A GPU is mainly used for permanent long-term data storage. | X | A GPU (Graphics Processing Unit) handles graphics and parallel computation, not storage.
An IP address identifies a device on a network. | O | An IP address is a numeric label that identifies a device so data can be routed to it.
Python is a type of computer hardware. | X | Python is a programming language, which is software, not a physical hardware component.
The kilobyte, megabyte, and gigabyte are units of digital storage. | O | These are increasingly large units used to measure digital data and storage capacity.
Cache memory is slower than main memory (RAM). | X | Cache is small, very fast memory placed close to the CPU, faster than main RAM.
A URL specifies the address of a resource on the web. | O | A URL (Uniform Resource Locator) tells a browser where to find a web resource.
Open-source software keeps its source code hidden from the public. | X | Open-source software makes its source code publicly available to view and modify.
A bug is an error or flaw in a computer program. | O | A bug is a defect that makes a program behave incorrectly or unexpectedly.
Encryption makes data easier for anyone to read. | X | Encryption scrambles data so only those with the correct key can read it.
The operating system manages a computer's hardware and software resources. | O | The operating system coordinates hardware, memory, and programs so they work together.
A hard disk drive (HDD) loses all its data when the computer is turned off. | X | An HDD is non-volatile storage, so it keeps data even without power.
A pixel is the smallest unit of a digital image. | O | A pixel is a single tiny dot of color; many pixels together form a digital image.
The World Wide Web and the Internet are exactly the same thing. | X | The Internet is the underlying network; the Web is one service of many that runs on top of it.
A loop is used to repeat a set of instructions in a program. | O | A loop runs the same block of code multiple times until a condition is met.
Malware is software designed to protect your computer from threats. | X | Malware is malicious software meant to harm or exploit systems; protective tools are antivirus or security software.
A variable stores data that can change during a program's execution. | O | A variable is a named location in memory whose value can be updated as a program runs.
A router's only job is to print documents. | X | A router forwards data between networks; printing is done by a printer.
Cloud computing delivers computing services over the Internet. | O | Cloud computing provides storage, servers, and software on demand over the Internet.
A boolean value can hold any whole number. | X | A boolean can hold only one of two values, true or false.
Backing up data helps protect against data loss. | O | Keeping backups means you can recover files if the original is lost or damaged.
Solid-state drives (SSDs) store data on spinning magnetic disks. | X | SSDs use flash memory with no moving parts; spinning magnetic disks are used by HDDs.
A database is an organized collection of data. | O | A database stores data in a structured way so it can be searched and managed efficiently.
A single bit can represent four different values. | X | A single bit has only two possible values, 0 or 1.
